&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/PDFBOX-2244&quot; title=&quot;java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException in callothersubr&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;PDFBOX-2244&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;PDFBOX-2244&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;: Handle out-of-order array indexes&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14086611" author="jahewson" created="Tue, 5 Aug 2014 18:53:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;That was a tricky one, the Type 1 font file contained out-of-order array indexes:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;/Subrs 241 array
dup 0 15 RD &amp;lt;binary data&amp;gt; noaccess put
dup 1 9 RD &amp;lt;binary data&amp;gt;ï¿½ noaccess put
dup 10 25 RD &amp;lt;binary data&amp;gt; noaccess put
etc...
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This defines elements 0, 1 and 10 of the array, later on elements 2..9 get defined too. This is legal but it wasn&apos;t handled in the parser as most fonts write there arrays in order (unsurprisingly).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
